</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=farnoak>Farnoak</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(5/17/02 12:56:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm43.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=86.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Warriors vs Paladins</span><hr size=1> Warriors are a very focused class.  They tank, they do damage, they taunt.  That's about it.  As a result, they do these things very well.  <br>
<br>
Warriors are the best tanks in the game and their advantage in tanking increases as they level.  Why?  Warriors get more hps per point of stamina than any other class in the game.  Warriors receive bonuses to hitpoints every 10 levels that no other class receives.  Warriors gain 1.6 points of AC for every AC on their armor.  Paladins and Shadowknights get only 1.5.  Warriors also have access to the evasive and defensive disciplines which make them hands down the kings of tanking in high end raid encounters.<br>
<br>
Given weapons of similar quality, Warriors will do about 20-30% more damage than a paladin or shadowknight, spells and pets included.  The reason for this is their ability to dual wield extremely good ratio one handed weapons and the damage bonus for level that applies to the main hand.  The higer the level, the more often dual wield fires and the higher the bonus you receive every time your main hand hits.  Being able to swing low delay weapons through dual wielding increases this advantage.  Again, these benefits are seen more in the higher level game, espeically at level 60 when the warrior gets his last bonus to damage and triple attack.<br>
<br>
There really is no right or wrong choice between Warrior, Paladin, and Shadowknight.  All three are very capable tanks for grinds.  <br>
<br>
Paladins and Shadowknights will bring more to a grind group if that group is lacking some of the classes that their spells make up for.  The paladin shines in groups against undead, groups against casting mobs where stun can make a tremendous difference, in groups where this is no enchanter where root parking is a necessity, or in groups with no cleric where a low level res is better than no res, and they can use their heals to help top off the group, thus saving shaman or druid mana.  <br>
<br>
A Shadowknight shines in a group with no snarer, or in a group where a wide variety of pulling styles is necessary.  A SK brings invis to both living and dead, long range pull spells, snares, and feign death.  If there is no necromancer in the group, the Shadowknight can also augment his damage with DoTs.<br>
<br>
The warrior is the only one of the three, however, that serves the main tank role for very high end encounters.  For end level raids, Paladins add value through DA, Wave of Prexus (a fantastic group heal), buffs (Brell's mountainous barrier), and melee damage.  Shadowknights provide value with their ability to feign death and their melee damage.<br>
